# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: couchbase
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] Markdown versions of all docs pages are available by replacing `.html` with `.md`.
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] Couchbase Server is an open source, distributed data-platform.
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] It stores data as *items*, each of which has a *key* and a *value*.
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] Sub-millisecond data operations are provided by powerful services for querying and indexing, and by a feature-rich, document-oriented query-language, SQL++.
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] Multiple instances of Couchbase Server can be combined into a single *cluster*.
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] A *Cluster Manager* program coordinates all node-activities, and provides a simple, cluster-wide interface to all clients.
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] Cluster administration is supported by a graphical, web-based administration console; as well as by REST and command-line interfaces.
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] Individual nodes can be added, removed, and replaced as appropriate, with no down-time required for the cluster as a whole.
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] Data can be retained either in memory only, or in both memory and storage, as judged appropriate by the administrator.
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] Data can be replicated across the nodes of the cluster, to ensure that node-loss (or even rack-loss) does not entail data-loss.
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] Data items can also be selectively replicated across data centers; for the purpose either of backup only, or of simultaneous, multi-geo application-access.
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] Couchbase Server provides multiple *Services*.
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] These can be deployed, maintained, and provisioned independently of one another, so as to allow *Multi-Dimensional Scaling*.
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] Such a deployment might indeed be well-suited to a pure development context; with little or no distinction required between individual services, in terms of workloads, priorities, and corresponding resource-allocations.
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] This production deployment would therefore anticipate a greater workload being placed on the Data and Index Services than on the Query and Search.
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] Further information on Couchbase Server’s technology high-points and business benefits can be found in Couchbase Server.
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] This section of the Couchbase documentation-set allows the administrator or developer to learn about the principal features of Couchbase Server at an architectural and conceptual level.
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] For detailed information on practical administration procedures, see the Overview provided for management documentation.
[src:couchbase/architecture-overview] Use the navigation bar at the left, to access additional documentation, covering other aspects of Couchbase technology; including installation, development, and integration.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Couchbase Server provided client protocol compatibility with memcached, but added disk persistence, data replication, live cluster reconfiguration, rebalancing and multitenancy with data partitioning.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Membase was developed by several leaders of the memcached project, who had founded a company, NorthScale, to develop a key-value store with the simplicity, speed, and scalability of memcached, but also the storage, persistence and querying capabilities of a database.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] The original membase source code was contributed by NorthScale, and project co-sponsors Zynga and Naver Corporation (then known as NHN) to a new project on membase.org in June 2010.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] On February 8, 2011, the Membase project founders and Membase, Inc. announced a merger with CouchOne (a company with many of the principal players behind CouchDB) with an associated project merger.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] The merged company was called Couchbase, Inc.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] In January 2012, Couchbase released Couchbase Server 1.8.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] In September of 2012, Orbitz said it had changed some of its systems to use Couchbase.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] In December of 2012, Couchbase Server 2.0 (announced in July 2011) was released and included a new JSON document store, indexing and querying, incremental MapReduce and replication across data centers.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Every Couchbase node consists of a data service, index service, query service, and cluster manager component.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Starting with the 4.0 release, the three services can be distributed to run on separate nodes of the cluster if needed.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] In the parlance of Eric Brewer's CAP theorem, Couchbase is normally a CP type system meaning it provides consistency and partition tolerance, or it can be set up as an AP system with multiple clusters.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] The cluster manager supervises the configuration and behavior of all the servers in a Couchbase cluster.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] It configures and supervises inter-node behavior like managing replication streams and re-balancing operations.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] It also provides metric aggregation and consensus functions for the cluster, and a RESTful cluster management interface.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] The cluster manager uses the Erlang programming language and the Open Telecom Platform.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Data replication within the nodes of a cluster can be controlled with several parameters.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] In December of 2012, support was added for replication between different data centers.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] The data manager stores and retrieves documents in response to data operations from applications.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] It asynchronously writes data to disk after acknowledging to the client.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] In version 1.7 and later, applications can optionally ensure data is written to more than one server or to disk before acknowledging a write to the client.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Parameters define item ages that affect when data is persisted, and how max memory and migration from main-memory to disk is handled.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] It supports working sets greater than a memory quota per "node" or "bucket".
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] External systems can subscribe to filtered data streams, supporting, for example, full text search indexing, data analytics or archiving.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] A document is the most basic unit of data manipulation in Couchbase Server.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Documents are stored in JSON document format with no predefined schemas.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Couchbase Server includes a built-in multi-threaded object-managed cache that implements memcached compatible APIs such as get, set, delete, append, prepend etc.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Couchbase Server has a tail-append storage design that is immune to data corruption, OOM killers or sudden loss of power.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Data is written to the data file in an append-only manner, which enables Couchbase to do mostly sequential writes for update, and provide an optimized access patterns for disk I/O.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] A performance benchmark done by Altoros in 2012, compared Couchbase Server with other technologies.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Cisco Systems published a benchmark that measured the latency and throughput of Couchbase Server with a mixed workload in 2012.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Couchbase Server is a packaged version of Couchbase's open source software technology and is available in a community edition without recent bug fixes with an Apache 2.0 license and an edition for commercial use.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Couchbase Server builds are available for Ubuntu, Debian, Red Hat, SUSE, Oracle Linux, Microsoft Windows and macOS operating systems.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Couchbase has supported software developers' kits for the programming languages .NET, PHP, Ruby, Python, C, Node.js, Java, Go, and Scala.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] A query language called SQL++ (formerly called N1QL), is used for manipulating the JSON data in Couchbase, just like SQL manipulates data in RDBMS.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] It has SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, MERGE statements to operate on JSON data.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] It was initially announced in March 2015 as "SQL for documents".
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] The SQL++ data model is non-first normal form (N1NF) with support for nested attributes and domain-oriented normalization.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] The SQL++ data model is also a proper superset and generalization of the relational model.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Couchbase Mobile / Couchbase Lite is a mobile database providing data replication.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Couchbase Lite added support for **Vector Search** in version 3.2, allowing cloud to edge support for vector search in mobile applications.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Couchbase began as an evolution of Memcached, a high-speed data cache, and can be used as a drop-in replacement for Memcached, providing high availability for memcached application without code changes.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Couchbase is used to support applications where a flexible data model, easy scalability, and consistent high performance are required, such as tracking real-time user activity or providing a store of user preferences or online applications.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Couchbase Mobile, which stores data locally on devices (usually mobile devices) is used to create “offline-first” applications that can operate when a device is not connected to a network and synchronize with Couchbase Server once a network connection is re-established.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] The Catalyst Lab at Northwestern University uses Couchbase Mobile to support the Evo application, a healthy lifestyle research program where data is used to help participants improve dietary quality, physical activity, stress, or sleep.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Amadeus uses Couchbase with Apache Kafka to support their “open, simple, and agile” strategy to consume and integrate data on loyalty programs for airline and other travel partners.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] Starting in 2012, it played a role in LinkedIn's caching systems, including backend caching for recruiter and jobs products, counters for security defense mechanisms, for internal applications.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] For caching, Couchbase competes with Memcached and Redis.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] For document databases, Couchbase competes with other document-oriented database systems.
[src:couchbase/couchbase-server] It is commonly compared with MongoDB, Amazon DynamoDB, Oracle RDBMS, DataStax, Google Bigtable, MariaDB, IBM Cloudant, Redis Enterprise, SingleStore, and MarkLogic.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] A **document-oriented database**, or **document store**, is a computer program and data storage system designed for storing, retrieving, and managing document-oriented information, also known as semi-structured data.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are one of the main categories of NoSQL databases, and the popularity of the term "document-oriented database" has grown alongside the adoption of NoSQL itself.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] XML databases are a subclass of document-oriented databases optimized for XML documents.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Graph databases are similar, but add another layer, the *relationship*, which allows them to link documents for rapid traversal.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are conceptually an extension of the key–value store, another type of NoSQL database.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] In key-value stores, data is treated as opaque by the database, whereas document-oriented systems exploit the internal structure of documents to extract metadata and optimize storage and queries.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Although in practice the distinction can be minimal due to modern tooling, document stores are designed to provide a richer programming experience with modern programming techniques.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Document databases differ significantly from traditional relational databases (RDBs).
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Relational databases store data in predefined tables, often requiring an object to be split across multiple tables.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document databases store all information for a given object in a single document, with each document potentially having a unique structure.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] This design eliminates the need for object-relational mapping when loading data into the database.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] The central concept of a document-oriented database is the notion of a *document*.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Although implementations vary in their specific definitions, document-oriented databases generally treat documents as self-contained units that encapsulate and encode data in a standardized format.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Common encoding formats include XML, YAML, JSON, as well as binary representations such as BSON.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document store are equivalent to the programming concept of an object.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] They are not required to adhere to a fixed schema, and documents within the same collection may contain different fields or structures.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Fields may be optional, and documents of the same logical type may differ in composition.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] The two example documents share some structural elements but also contain unique fields.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] The structure, text, and other data within each document are collectively referred to as the document's content and can be accessed or modified using retrieval or editing operations.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Unlike relational databases, in which each record contains the same fields and unused fields are left empty, document-oriented databases do not require uniform fields across documents.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] This design allows new information to be added to some documents without affecting the structure of others.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Document databases often support the storage of additional metadata alongside the document content.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Such metadata may relate to organizational features, security, indexing, or other implementation-specific features.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] The core operations supported by a document-oriented database for manipulating documents are similar to those in other databases.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Although terminology is not perfectly standardized, these operations are generally recognized as Create, Read, Update, and Delete (CRUD).
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document-oriented database are addressed via a unique identifier.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] This identifier, often a string, URI, or path, can be used to retrieve the document from the database.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Most document stores maintain an index on the key to optimize retrieval, and in some implementations the key is required when creating or inserting a new document.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] In addition to key-based access, document-oriented databases typically provide an API or query language that enables retrieval based on document content or associated metadata.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] For example, a query may return all documents with a specific field matching a given value.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] The available query features, indexing options, and performance characteristics vary across implementations.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Document stores differ from key-value stores in that they exploit the internal structure and metadata of stored documents.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] In many key-value stores, values are treated as opaque or "black-box" data, meaning the database system does not interpret their internal structure.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] By contrast, document-oriented databases can classify and interpret document content.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Document databases typically provide mechanisms for updating or editing the content or metadata of a document.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Updates may involve replacing the entire document or modifying individual elements or fields within the document.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] These organizational structures may differ between logical and physical representations (e.g. on disk or in memory).
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] A document-oriented database can be viewed as a specialized form of key-value store, which is itself a category of NoSQL database.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] In a basic key-value store, the stored value is typically treated as opaque by the database system.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] By contrast, a document-oriented database provides APIs or a query and update language that allows queries and modifications based on the internal structure of the document.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] For users who do not require advanced query, retrieval, or update capabilities, the distinction between document-oriented databases and key-value stores may be minimal.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Some search engine and information retrieval systems, such as Apache Solr and Elasticsearch, provide document storage and support core document operations.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] As a result, they may meet certain functional definitions of a document-oriented database, although their primary design goals differ.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] In a relational database, data is organized into predefined types represented as tables.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Each table contains rows (records) with a fixed set of columns (fields), so all records in a table share the same structure.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Administrators typically define indexes on selected fields to improve query performance.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] A central principle of relational database design is database normalization, in which data that might otherwise be repeated is stored in separate tables and linked using keys.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] When records in different tables are related, a foreign key is used to associate them.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] For example, an address book application may store a contact's name, image, phone numbers, mailing addresses, and email addresses.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] In a normalized relational design, separate tables might be created for contacts, phone numbers, and email addresses.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] The phone number table would include a foreign key referencing the associated contact.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] To reconstruct a complete contact record, the database retrieves related information from each table using the foreign keys and combines it into a single record.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] In contrast, a document-oriented database stores all data related to an object within a single document, and stored in the database as a single entry.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] In the address book example,the contact's name, image, and contact information may be stored together in one document.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] The document is retrieved using a unique key, and all related information is returned together, without needing to look up multiple tables.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] A key difference between the document-oriented and relational models is that the data formats are not predefined in the document case.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] In most cases, any sort of document can be stored in a database, and documents can change in type and form over time.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] For example, a new field such as COUNTRY_FLAG can be added to new documents as they are inserted without affecting existing documents.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] To aid retrieval, document-oriented systems generally allow the administrator to provide hints to the database for locating certain types of information.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] These hints work in a similar fashion to indexes in relational databases.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Many systems also allow additional metadata outside the content of the document itself, such as tagging entries as part of an address book, which enables retrieval of related information, for instance, all the address book entries.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] This provides functionality similar to a table, but separates the concept (categories of data) from its physical implementation (tables).
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] In the traditional normalized relational model, objects in the database are represented as separate rows of data, with no inherent structure beyond what is defined in the tables.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] This can create difficulties when translating programming objects to and from their corresponding database rows, a challenge known as object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document stores often map programming objects directly into the database, preserving much of their internal structure.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Databases using this approach are frequently described as NoSQL systems.
[src:couchbase/document-oriented-database] Most XML databases are document-oriented databases.
[src:couchbase/home-index] Couchbase is a distributed document database with a powerful search engine and in-built operational and analytical capabilities.
[src:couchbase/home-index] It brings the power of NoSQL to the edge and provides fast, efficient bidirectional synchronization of data between the edge and the cloud.
